  <info>
    <title>Upgrading to a new release</title><!-- can be changed via merge
in the assembly -->
    <!-- add author's e-mail -->
    <meta name="maintainer" content="jsindelarova@suse.com" its:translate="no"/>
    <abstract><!-- can be changed via merge in the assembly -->
      <para>
       The topic covers the upgrade steps.
      </para>
    </abstract>
  </info>
  <para>
    Before starting the upgrade procedure, make sure the following requirements are met:
  </para>
  <variablelist>
     <varlistentry>
      <term>Internet connection</term>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          Make sure that your machine has network connection throughout the entire upgrade process.
        </para>
      </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
  <varlistentry>
    <term>&productnameshort; 5.5</term>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          Upgrade to 6.0 is possible only from the 5.5 version. If you have older version, upgrade
          to 5.5 first (see the <link xlink:href="https://documentation.suse.com/sle-micro/5.5/html/SLE-Micro-all/book-upgrade-slemicro.html">upgrade guide</link>).
        </para>
      </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      </variablelist>
      <para>
        To start the upgrade process, proceed as follows:
      </para>
      <procedure>
        <step>
          <para>
            Run the command:
          </para>
          <screen>&prompt.sudo;<command>transactional-update migration</command></screen>
          <para>
            Invoking the command creates a new snapshot and refreshes the repositories.
          </para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Enter a number of the migration target.</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>
            A list of packages to be changed is displayed. Press <literal>y</literal> to continue.
          </para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>
            If the process completes successfully, reboot your machine:
          </para>
          <screen>
            &prompt.sudo;<command>reboot</command>
          </screen>
        </step>
      </procedure>
      <note>
        <title>Failed upgrade</title>
        <para>
          If the upgrade procedure fails, you can roll back your system to a prevous snapshot.
          Refer to the <link
          xlink:href="https://documentation.suse.com/smart/systems-management/html/transactional-updates-marble/index.html#tr-up-rollback">roll-back
          procedure</link>.
        </para>
      </note>
</topic>
